<article>
    <h1>A ca&#xAD;su&#xAD;alty of US politi&#xAD;cians&#x2019; deep&#xAD;en&#xAD;ing mis&#xAD;trust of China</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20200804/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-08-04"><time>2020-08-04</time></a>
        - <span>TOPOF THE NEWS</span>
        - <span role="byline">Nir&#xAD;mal Ghosh&#xD;&#xA;US Bureau Chief In Washington nir&#xAD;mal@sph.com.sg</span>
    </section>

    <p>The United States’ move to ban or oth­er­wise cut off the pop­u­lar Chi­nese-owned so­cial me­dia app Tik­Tok is part of a con­certed ef­fort to cut link­ages with China that can be ex­ploited to gather Amer­i­cans’ data – or have any kind of in­flu­ence in Amer­i­can so­ci­ety.</p>
    <p>The the­ory is that be­cause Tik­Tok is sub­ject to Chi­nese law, the com­pany can be com­pelled by the Chi­nese gov­ern­ment to pro­vide ac­cess to user data. There is also sep­a­rate con­cern over whether Tik­Tok uses con­tent-mod­er­a­tion poli­cies and prac­tices that serve the pref­er­ences of the Chi­nese Com­mu­nist Party.</p>
    <p>Tik­Tok, though, ar­gues that data from US users re­mains ex­clu­sively in its servers lo­cated in Amer­ica.</p>
    <p>And it is dif­fi­cult, ab­sent hard ev­i­dence of data theft or trans­fer, to sep­a­rate the Tik­Tok is­sue from ris­ing anti-Chi­nese sen­ti­ment in Amer­ica – al­most to the point of xeno­pho­bia – as the vol­ume on the per­ceived China threat is turned up by Pres­i­dent Don­ald Trump’s re-elec­tion cam­paign.</p>
    <p>“Don­ald Trump… has con­structed an en­emy that can be con­stantly vil­i­fied, and whose al­leged in­ten­tions and ac­tions to end Amer­i­can pri­macy may gen­er­ate fear psy­chosis among Amer­i­can vot­ers,” hon­orary re­search fel­low Atul Bhardwaj and pro­fes­sor of in­ter­na­tional pol­i­tics In­der­jeet Par­mar, both at City, Univer­sity of Lon­don, wrote in the Eco­nomic and Po­lit­i­cal Weekly.</p>
    <p>“For... Pres­i­dent Trump, hit­ting China hard is good pol­i­tics as the elec­tion ap­proaches,” the Eura­sia Group said in an e-mail.</p>
    <p>“He has lit­tle good news right now on the econ­omy or coro­n­avirus, but sus­pi­cions of China en­joy strong bi­par­ti­san and pop­u­lar sup­port th­ese days.”</p>
    <p>Tik­Tok is not the first Chi­nese com­pany to en­counter prob­lems in the US. Ear­lier this year, gam­ing com­pany Bei­jing Kun­lun Tech had to sell the dat­ing app Grindr for US$620 mil­lion (S$854 mil­lion) af­ter be­ing or­dered to di­vest by the Com­mit­tee on For­eign In­vest­ment in the United States (CFIUS).</p>
    <p>Un­der the Trump ad­min­is­tra­tion, the CFIUS has ac­quired a wider man­date to scru­ti­nise for­eign in­vest­ments for na­tional se­cu­rity im­pli­ca­tions. And in Jan­uary, it was given more power – un­der the For­eign In­vest­ment Risk Re­view Mod­erni­sa­tion Act of 2018 – to re­view deals based on the de­gree of con­trol of a for­eign in­vestor.</p>
    <p>But even be­fore that – in 2018 – CFIUS had forced China’s Ant Fi­nan­cial to scrap plans to buy MoneyGram In­ter­na­tional over con­cerns about the safety of US cit­i­zens’ data.</p>
    <p>On Sun­day, Sec­re­tary of State Mike Pom­peo told Fox News: “Th­ese Chi­nese soft­ware com­pa­nies do­ing busi­ness in the United States, whether it’s Tik­Tok or WeChat… are feed­ing data di­rectly to the Chi­nese Com­mu­nist Party, their na­tional se­cu­rity ap­pa­ra­tus.”</p>
    <p>He added: “It could be their fa­cial recog­ni­tion pat­tern. It could be in­for­ma­tion about their res­i­dence, their phone num­bers, their friends, who they’re con­nected to. Th­ese are true na­tional se­cu­rity is­sues.”</p>
    <p>Trea­sury Sec­re­tary Steven Mnuchin has also said Tik­Tok “can­not stay in its cur­rent for­mat. The Pres­i­dent can ei­ther force a sale or ban the app”.</p>
    <p>In June, In­dia’s Prime Min­is­ter Naren­dra Modi banned Tik­Tok and other Chi­nese apps from the coun­try’s mar­ket af­ter a skir­mish on the bor­der be­tween Chi­nese and In­dian troops left In­dian sol­diers dead and plunged re­la­tions with Bei­jing to a new low. The ban drew im­me­di­ate praise from Mr Pom­peo for In­dia’s “clean apps” ap­proach.</p>
    <p>An­a­lysts, mean­while, are won­der­ing what else may be vul­ner­a­ble to a US ban. Many Chi­nese-owned apps are used in the US, in­clud­ing Ten­cent’s WeChat.</p>
    <p>In the case of Tik­Tok, which has a mil­lion users in the US, an out­right ban may also make Mr Trump more un­pop­u­lar with younger vot­ers. A sale of the firm – re­port­edly un­der dis­cus­sion with Mi­crosoft – would be a win-win, with the strate­gic ob­jec­tive of cut­ting off from China achieved.</p>
    <p>For... Pres­i­dent Trump, hit­ting China hard is good pol­i­tics as the elec­tion ap­proaches... He has lit­tle good news right now on the econ­omy or coro­n­avirus, but sus­pi­cions of China en­joy strong bi­par­ti­san and pop­u­lar sup­port ’’ th­ese days.</p>
    <p>THE EURA­SIA GROUP</p>

